record_data.record_plain_text:
Wholesale Power Sales Tariff
1 Definitions
The following words or terms used in this Tariff shall have the meanings indicated below:
1.1 Business Day(s): any day which is not a Saturday, Sunday or holiday as declared by the North American Electric Reliability Council or the successor thereto.
1.2 Customer: an ELIGIBLE ENTITY which has entered into a SERVICE AGREEMENT under this TARIFF.
1.3 Eligible Entity: any customer authorized by state, federal, Canadian or Mexican law to purchase energy for resale. Ultimate consumers of electric utility service (ie., retail customers) are not ELIGIBLE ENTITIES under this TARIFF.
1.4 Energy: power product(s) provided to a Customer, which may be comprised of capacity and/or energy, which SELLER chooses to sell to a Customer at a negotiated market based rate under this Tariff. Energy may also include certain transmission rights and ancillary services, as set forth under this TARIFF.
1.5 Federal Power Act: that Federal Power Act, 16 U.S.C. Section; 792 "et seq.", as it is now or may be amended in the future, or any successor thereto.
1.6 FERC: the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, or its successor having regulatory jurisdiction over this TARIFF.
1.7 MWh: Megawatthour or Megawatthours.
1.8 Seller: the provider of service under this TARIFF.
1.9 Service Agreement: the initial agreement, and any amendments or supplements thereto, between the CUSTOMER and SELLER for service under this TARIFF.
1.10 Tariff: this TARIFF as it is now or as it may be amended or supplemented from time to time in accordance with Section 8 hereof.
1.11 Transaction: a separately-arranged reservation or sale of ENERGY or sale, assignment or transfer of transmission rights to a CUSTOMER under this TARIFF.
2 Purpose and Applicability of Tariff
2.1 Purpose: This TARIFF establishes terms and conditions under which SELLER will from time to time, at its sole discretion, make ENERGY available for sale.
2.2 Applicability: Service under this TARIFF is available to any ELIGIBLE ENTITY in accordance with, and subject to, the terms and conditions contained in this TARIFF.
3 Credit
3.1 Credit: Without satisfactory credit information or financial guarantees, SELLER shall not be required to enter into a Service Agreement or TRANSACTION under this TARIFF.
3.1.1 Creditworthiness: In conjunction with the execution of the SERVICE AGREEMENT and throughout the term of the SERVICE AGREEMENT, SELLER shall have the right to seek from the ELIGIBLE ENTITY the following financial information necessary for SELLER to review the ELIGIBLE ENTITY'S creditworthiness, financial responsibility, or performance viability:
(a) current financial statements, annual reports, other publicly available reports and filings;
(b) a bank reference and trade references; and
(c) verification of the ELIGIBLE ENTITY'S solvency or status in bankruptcy.
3.1.2 Additional Information: SELLER may request such other information as it determines may reasonably be required to evaluate the ELIGIBLE ENTITY'S creditworthiness for service pursuant to this TARIFF.
3.1.3 Financial Guarantees: In the event that the ELIGIBLE ENTITY does not provide credit information requested by SELLER, or such information is not satisfactory to SELLER in its sole discretion, then the ELIGIBLE ENTITY shall provide one of the following payment guarantees:
(a) an irrevocable letter of credit applicable to SELLER;
(b) a security interest in collateral or other form of security interest found by SELLER to be acceptable; or
(c) a guarantee by a person or another entity who satisfies SELLER's credit appraisal criteria.
3.2 No Warranty: By executing a SERVICE AGREEMENT with any ELIGIBLE ENTITY, SELLER does not warrant that it has any ENERGY available for sale hereunder and does not commit to enter into any individual TRANSACTION with any ELIGIBLE ENTITY unless otherwise stated in the SERVICE AGREEMENT.
3.3 Agreement: By signing a SERVICE AGREEMENT, the ELIGIBLE ENTITY agrees to take and pay for, and SELLER agrees to supply, such ENERGY as is mutually agreed upon, subject to the terms and conditions of this TARIFF as amended from time to time, and such other terms and conditions agreed upon by SELLER and the CUSTOMER under a Transaction and subject to the action of FERC. In addition, both SELLER and CUSTOMER agree to comply with all applicable requirements established by any entity having authority with respect to regional power transactions.
3.4 Cancellation: SELLER reserves the right to cancel the SERVICE AGREEMENT between SELLER and the CUSTOMER consistent with the provisions of FERC's regulations governing notices of cancellation or termination. Notwithstanding the preceding, SELLER shall not have the right to cancel a SERVICE AGREEMENT until all TRANSACTIONS under such SERVICE AGREEMENT have been completed except that SELLER may suspend and terminate an existing Transaction(s) if:
(a) CUSTOMER files a voluntary petition, or has an involuntary petition filed against it, for bankruptcy under the United States Bankruptcy Code, 11 U.S.C. Section;Section; 101 et. seq., or similar state insolvency laws;
(b) CUSTOMER otherwise becomes insolvent or fails to meet its payment obligations when due;
(c) the CUSTOMER fails to provide financial information and/or SELLER reasonably determined that CUSTOMER is not creditworthy; provided, however, that SELLER may agree to continue a TRANSACTION if CUSTOMER prepays for the TRANSACTION or furnishes good and sufficient security of a continuing nature in an amount at least equal to the cost of such TRANSACTION; or
(d) In the event of non-payment of a Bill within five (5) BUSINESS DAYS after written notice of such failure is received by the Customer, SELLER shall have the right to suspend or terminate an existing TRANSACTION(s).
3.5 Netting: If SELLER and the CUSTOMER are each required to pay an amount on the same payment due date, in the same month for TRANSACTIONS under this TARIFF and sales by the CUSTOMER to SELLER under separate agreement(s) designated by the parties, then such amounts with respect to each party may be aggregated and the parties may discharge their obligations to pay through netting, in which case the party owing the greater aggregate amount will pay to the other party the difference between the amounts owed. Each party reserves to itself all rights, set-offs, counterclaims and other remedies and/or defenses to which it is or may be entitled, arising from or out of this TARIFF or the CUSTOMER'S Agreement(s). All outstanding TRANSACTIONS and the obligations to make payment in connection therewith or under this TARIFF or the CUSTOMER'S Agreement(s) may be offset against each other or set off or recouped therefrom.
4 Nature and Priority of Service
4.1 Transactions Voluntary: Upon execution of a SERVICE AGREEMENT by CUSTOMER, SELLER shall, from time to time, make ENERGY available in varying amounts for purchase or reservation by that CUSTOMER, subject to SELLER's sole determination of the availability thereof. Entry into all TRANSACTIONS under this TARIFF shall be voluntary.
4.2 Priority: The priority and nature of service for any TRANSACTION shall be negotiated between SELLER and CUSTOMER.
4.3 Price Structure: Use of either a reservation or as-delivered price structure is for economic and operational convenience, and does not change the nature of the ENERGY sold under this TARIFF. The price structure of ENERGY under a TRANSACTION shall be negotiated in accordance with Section 4.2 of this TARIFF and shall not be interpreted so as to alter the priority of ENERGY delivery negotiated in a TRANSACTION.
4.4 Ancillary Services:
PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection.
New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc.
New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non- spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc.
California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO.
4.5 Ancillary Services - Third Party Provider: Third-party ancillary services: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve-Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization.
5 Delivery Point
5.1 Delivery Point: All deliveries of ENERGY hereunder will be made at delivery point(s) designated by mutual agreement of SELLER and CUSTOMER for the particular TRANSACTION at the time the TRANSACTION is scheduled or as otherwise designated by mutual agreement. A delivery point may include existing point(s) at which SELLER's and the CUSTOMER's systems interconnect or point(s) where SELLER and CUSTOMER, through agreement(s) one or both may have with others, have the right to deliver or receive ENERGY.
5.2 Transmission: SELLER and CUSTOMER need not be directly interconnected. Unless otherwise agreed, the CUSTOMER shall have the responsibility for obtaining or providing all necessary transmission and ancillary services after the delivery point. SELLER shall have the right to receive assurances satisfactory to it that all necessary transmission arrangements are in place prior to committing to any TRANSACTIONS pursuant to this TARIFF.
6 Scheduling and Operating Procedures
6.1 Procedures: Throughout the term of this TARIFF, SELLER shall maintain in effect scheduling and operating procedures governing the provision of service hereunder. Such procedures shall specify content, deadlines, and contact points for communications which SELLER may require for scheduling, operating, reporting, and accounting purposes, and shall be consistent with the requirements established by any entity having authority with respect to regional power transactions.
6.2 Advance Determination: Prior to the commencement of a TRANSACTION, SELLER and CUSTOMER shall agree upon starting date and time, duration, quantity, price structure, performance penalties, if applicable, and other specific terms of the TRANSACTION.
6.3 Scheduling: Whenever SELLER and a CUSTOMER enter into a TRANSACTION for ENERGY pursuant to this TARIFF, the CUSTOMER shall arrange with SELLER to schedule all deliveries of ENERGY hereunder.
7 Charges
7.1 Generation Charges: For TRANSACTIONS under this TARIFF, each CUSTOMER shall pay a monthly charge calculated as the sum for the month of the products of the MWh delivered by SELLER in each hour of the month multiplied by the energy charge rate for the same hours agreed upon prior to the TRANSACTION pursuant to Section 6.2.
7.2 Other Charges: Unless otherwise agreed, CUSTOMER will reimburse SELLER for any third party transmission and ancillary services costs after the delivery point incurred by or billed to SELLER in providing service under this TARIFF.
8 General Terms and Conditions
8.1 Dedication of Facilities: No undertaking by SELLER or CUSTOMER under any provision of this TARIFF shall be deemed to constitute the dedication of SELLER's system or any portion thereof to the public, to the CUSTOMER, or to any other entity. It is understood and agreed that any such undertaking by SELLER or CUSTOMER shall cease upon termination of the TRANSACTION entered into under this TARIFF or cancellation of the SERVICE AGREEMENT.
8.2 Billing and Payments
8.2.1 Bills, Payments, Estimates, Interest, And Adjustments: A monthly billing statement ("Bill") shall be rendered by SELLER to CUSTOMER no later than the tenth (10th) day of the month following the month in which ENERGY was sold and shall be due and payable by CUSTOMER by wire transfer, to an account to be specified by SELLER, on the first BUSINESS DAY common to the parties following the ninth (9th) day after CUSTOMER receives Bill. Interest on unpaid amounts shall accrue daily from the due date of such unpaid amount until the date paid at a rate equal to 130% of the then current prime interest rate per annum of The Chase Manhattan Bank (National Association) or its successor. In the event that a Bill is rendered on an estimated basis, any adjustment for actual deliveries shall be made in a subsequent month's Bill. Each Bill shall be subject to adjustment for any other errors in arithmetic, computation, meter readings, or other errors until twelve months after the date the Bill was rendered.
8.2.2 Disputes: In the event a Bill or portion thereof, or any other claim or adjustment arising hereunder, is disputed, payment of the Bill in the amount rendered shall be made when due with written notice of the points in dispute being given to SELLER at that time. If it is subsequently determined or agreed that an adjustment to the Bill is appropriate, a revised Bill shall be prepared by SELLER. Any overpayment or underpayment shall bear interest (at the rate provided above) and shall be assessed from the time of said over or under payment to the date of issuance of the revised Bill or refund. Payment pursuant to the revised Bill shall be made as provided in the preceding paragraph.
8.3 Liability and Indemnification: Neither SELLER nor CUSTOMER shall be responsible to each other in tort (including negligence and strict liability), contract or otherwise for any loss, cost or damage of any kind which may result from or be caused by interruptions in service or deficiencies in the quality or quantity of service under this TARIFF unless agreed otherwise in a Transaction. SELLER and CUSTOMER expressly agree to indemnify, hold harmless and defend the other against all claims, liability, costs or expenses for loss, damage or injury to persons or property in any manner directly or indirectly connected with or growing out of the generation, transmission or distribution of electric energy on its own side of the delivery point hereunder. Nothing herein shall create, or be interpreted as creating, any standard of care with reference to, or any duty or liability to any person not a CUSTOMER hereunder.
8.4 Force Majeure: Nothing is this Section 8.4 shall be construed to limit SELLER's right to interrupt TRANSACTIONS under this TARIFF according to Section 4.2 hereof. SELLER and CUSTOMER shall use due diligence to perform their obligations under this TARIFF and the SERVICE AGREEMENT. However, neither SELLER nor Customer shall be considered to be in default of any of its obligations under a Transaction, except to make payment as specified in such Transaction in the event that either SELLER or CUSTOMER is delayed in or prevented from performing or carrying out its obligations under this TARIFF and any agreements or transactions hereunder in whole or in part by reason of any cause beyond the reasonable control of the party claiming Force Majeure, including, without limitation as to the nature or kind of events, sabotage, strikes, lockouts or other labor disputes, riots, disorders or civil disturbances, vandalism, acts of god, acts of public enemy, droughts, epidemics, earthquakes, floods, explosions, fires, storms, snow, hail, ice, lightning, wind, landslides, washouts, embargoes, acts of military authorities, actions or inactions of local, state, or federal legislative, judicial or regulatory agencies or other proper authorities, arrests, restraints, any of which by exercise of due diligence the party claiming the Force Majeure could not reasonably have been expected to avoid and which by the exercise of due diligence it has been unable to overcome. Neither SELLER nor Customer shall, however, be relieved of liability for failure of performance if such failure be due to causes arising out of its own negligence or due to removable or remediable causes which it fails to remove or remedy within a reasonable time period. The party encountering such delay or prevention shall notify the other as soon as reasonably possible of the delay or prevention and shall use due diligence to remove promptly the cause or causes thereof. In order to be relieved of obligations pursuant to this Section 8.4, neither SELLER nor CUSTOMER shall be required to settle any strike, walkout, lockout or other labor dispute on terms which, in the sole judgment of the party involved in the dispute, or contrary to its interest.
8.5 Records: SELLER and CUSTOMER shall each keep complete and accurate records of all transactions conducted pursuant to this TARIFF. SELLER and CUSTOMER shall maintain such records for a period of at least two years. SELLER and CUSTOMER, on a confidential basis in accordance with Section 8.12 of this TARIFF, shall make such records available for inspection and audit by an independent third party at reasonable times and places upon request. The party seeking access to such records shall pay all of the fees and expenses associated with the use of an independent third party auditor.
8.6 Successors and Assigns: Any SERVICE AGREEMENT shall be binding upon the parties thereto, their successors and assigns, on and after the effective date of such SERVICE AGREEMENT. Such SERVICE AGREEMENT may not be assigned in whole or in part to any third party, except to a successor acquiring substantially all the electric assets of SELLER or CUSTOMER, or to any entity affiliated with SELLER or any successor SELLER, without the written consent of SELLER or CUSTOMER. Such consent shall not be unreasonably withheld.
8.7. Notices: All notices provided pursuant to this TARIFF or any SERVICE AGREEMENT hereunder shall be in writing and addressed as set forth in the SERVICE AGREEMENT.
8.8 Regulation: The provision of service by SELLER under this TARIFF and any SERVICE AGREEMENT is subject to the jurisdiction of the FERC. Nothing contained in this TARIFF or any SERVICE AGREEMENT entered into hereunder shall be construed as affecting or limiting in any way the right of SELLER unilaterally to file with the FERC, or make application to the FERC for, changes in rates, charges, classifications, or service, or any rule or regulation relating hereto, in this TARIFF or any SERVICE AGREEMENT, under Section 205 of the FEDERAL POWER ACT pursuant to FERC's rules and regulations promulgated thereunder, or under other applicable statutes or regulations, unless the parties agree otherwise in writing under a TRANSACTION.
8.9 Term of Tariff: This TARIFF shall become effective on the date specified by FERC. However, if FERC or any reviewing court, in such order or in any separate order, imposes any condition, limitation or qualification under any of the provisions of the FEDERAL POWER ACT which, individually or in the aggregate, SELLER determined to be adverse to SELLER, then SELLER may, at its option, terminate this TARIFF in light of such FERC or court action. Otherwise, this TARIFF shall remain effective until terminated by SELLER upon thirty (30) days' notice and receipt of all regulatory approvals necessary for such termination.
8.10 After Termination or Cancellation: The applicable provisions of this TARIFF and any SERVICE AGREEMENT entered into under this TARIFF shall continue in effect after termination or cancellation thereof to the extent necessary to provide for final billing, billing adjustments and payments with respect to any CUSTOMER'S obligation to indemnify SELLER with regard to a covered claim associated with or arising out of events that occurred prior to the termination or cancellation of the CUSTOMER'S SERVICE AGREEMENT.
8.11 Governing Law: The validity and meaning of this TARIFF and any SERVICE AGREEMENT entered into hereunder shall be governed by the laws of the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania.
8.12 Confidentiality: SELLER and CUSTOMER shall treat as confidential all price and rate terms of any proposed or actual TRANSACTION hereunder as well as any other term thereof which may be designated by SELLER or CUSTOMER ("Confidential Matter"). Confidential Matter shall be for the sole and exclusive use of SELLER and CUSTOMER, and, subject to the provisions set forth below, neither SELLER nor CUSTOMER shall publish, disclose, or otherwise divulge the Confidential Matter to any person at any time without the prior written consent of the other unless the release of the Confidential Matter is pursuant to a requirement imposed by FERC or any other governmental or judicial body of competent jurisdiction. When either SELLER or CUSTOMER receives from any other entity or person a request for Confidential Matter, not then in the public domain, it shall inform the other of such request as soon as reasonably practicable. SELLER and CUSTOMER shall reasonably cooperate with each other in the exercise of any applicable rights to oppose the disclosure of the Confidential Matter to the requestor or to prevent the Confidential Matter from becoming part of the public domain. Confidential Matter need not be treated confidentially once it has passed into the public domain.
8.13 [Reserved]
8.14 Waiver: Any waiver at any time by SELLER or CUSTOMER of its rights with respect to any default under the TARIFF, or with respect to any other matters arising in connection with this TARIFF, shall not be considered a waiver with respect to any subsequent default or matter.
8.15 [Reserved]
8.16 Reporting: TRANSACTION prices charged by SELLER shall be reported in a manner consistent with FERC policies. Additionally, SELLER shall report in its quarterly reports the name of each Customer to whom SELLER sold, assigned or transferred any of SELLER's transmission rights.
8.17 Conflicts: In the case of any conflict between the TARIFF or a SERVICE AGREEMENT and the terms and conditions of a TRANSACTION, the terms and conditions of a TRANSACTION shall govern.
8.18 Tapes: SELLER shall have the right to tape record telephone conversations regarding any TRANSACTION or potential TRANSACTION. Each party consents to the recording of its telephone conversations without any further notice. Any such recordings may be used to prove the terms of a TRANSACTION completed in accordance with the provisions of this TARIFF.
8.19 Compliance with Commission Regulations: Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes seller to engage in affiliate sales under this tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this tariff.
8.20 Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority: The Commission granted waiver of the code of conduct and affiliate sales restrictions to Exelon affiliates in Exelon Generation Co., LLC, 93 FERC 61,140, at 61,426 (2000). See also Potomac Electric Power Co., 93 FERC 61,240 (2000).
8.21 Seller Category: Seller is a Category 1 seller in the Central, Northwest, Southeast, Southwest, and Southwest Power Pool regions, and a Category 2 seller in the Northeast region, as defined in 18 C.F.R. Section; 35.36(a).
